notes.body:
Losartan body model
losartan and exp3174 are excreted in urine; urinary excretion of losartan and exp3174, but low recoveries (~5% losartan, 6% exp3174 [Yasar2002a])
IV losartan [FDA]:
urine
total metabolites: 43.3 ± 8.4 % (urine);
losartan: 11.4 ± 4.0 % (urine)
e3174: 6.44 ± 2.45 % (urine)
other: 17.6 % (urine)
feces
total metabolites: 49.5 ± 13.3 % (feces);
losartan: 7.77 - 12.8 % (urine)
e3174: 6.92 - 13.38 % (urine)
other: ~16% (urine)
fast halflife of losartan (removal plasma in ~12hr) => no accumlation expected in multiple dosing
longer halflife, slower peaks of exp3174 (removal plasma in ~24hr) => accumulation
33-35 % bioavailability; 38.9 ± 14.7% [Lo1995]
55% of infused EXP3174 is recovered in urine; probably metabolization of the metabolite (in liver?) [Lo1995]
The content of this model has been carefully created in a manual research effort.

ul.li: exp3174 inhibits aldosterone secretion; probably via the inhibition of AT1 receptors, resulting in reduced aldosterone secretion. This is modelled via the fi dependency.
angiotensin II activates aldosterone secretion by binding to AT1 receptors

body.p: Organic Anion Transporting Polypeptide 2B1 (OATP2B1): Recent findings suggest that losartan is also a substrate for OATP2B1, a transporter that plays a crucial role in the uptake of various drugs into hepatocytes. This transporter facilitates the entry of losartan into liver cells, where it can be metabolized by cytochrome P450 enzymes. [perplexity] Assumption: fast transport.
Likely catalyzed CYP2C9 and CYP3A4. Currently only modified via CYP2C9 factor.
Formation of losartan glucuronides, likely via UGT enzymes. Assumption: e3174 metabolite is converted; not much information available on pathway.
